user_request: A love poem about eyes meeting across a crowded room.

revision_history.draft:
The crowd hums a low frequency,  
heat pooling in the marrow of my bones.  
Your gaze is a piston jammed between my ribs—  
I shift my weight, a gear grinding against the floor.  
The noise blooms louder, a static storm  
pricking my ears. My pulse, a faulty relay,  
flickers. The air smells of burnt coffee  
and metal fatigue. I blink, and the world  
reprograms itself—  
a circuit closes, but no light bulbs bloom.

final_poem:
The crowd hums a low frequency,  
heat pooling in my bones, a slow burn.  
Your gaze is a piston jammed between my ribs—  
I shift, a gear grinding, my weight a tremor.  
The noise blooms—a static storm,  
pricking my ears. My pulse, a faulty relay,  
flickers. The air reeks of burnt coffee,  
metal fatigue. I blink, and the world  
rewires itself—  
a circuit closes, but no light blooms.
